Preparing and Organizing Data for Display

Mahbubul Majumder, PhD
Feb 27, 2019

About data

  • What is data?

    • fact or information about some population

  • Types: mainly three types of data

    • Numerical/quantitative
      • Continuous: life time, income, distance etc.
      • Discrete: count data, number of accidents
    • Categorical/qualitative
      • ordered: income level (low, medium, high)
      • unordered: gender (male, female)
    • Dates

Organizing data

  • Can we always plot the data without reorganizing it?

  • There are three types of reorganizations

    • tidy data
    • reshape the data
    • transform the data

  • When data is received, the first step is to check if it violates the basic principles of tidy data.

  • Reshaping the data is needed when we want to map the variable to an aesthetic but variable is not explicitly available

  • Transforming is needed when some theoretical/ mathematical model is fitted or associated with the data

Long vs wide form data

  • How can we switch between long form and wide form of data

    • install.packages(rehsape2)
    • there are two functions
      • melt() melts data to long form
      • dcast() shapes molten data to wide form

  • cast() function has some other variations

    • acast() is for array type data
    • dcast() is for data frame

  • Package tidyr provides two functions to reshape data

    • spread() converts long form to wide form
    • gather() converts wide form to long form

Long vs wide form data

  • Converting wide to long form
mdat <- melt(wdat, 
             id = "year")
kable(mdat)
year variable value
2010 online-sale 20
2011 online-sale 24
2012 online-sale 35
2010 store-sale 25
2011 store-sale 31
2012 store-sale 40
  • Converting long to wide form
wdat <- dcast(mdat, 
          year~variable, 
          value.var = "value")
kable(wdat)
year online-sale store-sale
2010 20 25
2011 24 31
2012 35 40

  • Solution: generate scatterplot of rep1 vs rep2

    • we need to melt the data
    • we should not melt column time, treatment, subject and rep
    • finally cast the data as the form we want to create scatterplot

Molten French fries data

  • first we melt the french_fries data
molten_fries <- melt(french_fries, id=1:4)
head(molten_fries)

  time treatment subject rep variable value
1    1         1       3   1   potato   2.9
2    1         1       3   2   potato  14.0
3    1         1      10   1   potato  11.0
4    1         1      10   2   potato   9.9
5    1         1      15   1   potato   1.2
6    1         1      15   2   potato   8.8
  • now we need two variables rep1 and rep2 for the scatterplot
    • we can do this by casting this molten data
    • while casting we need to keep variables time treatment subject intact and fixed

Casting French fries data

  • we used formula time + treatment + subject + variable~rep
    • it allows us to fix variables time, treatment, subject and variable
    • it creates two new columns 1 and 2
cast_fries <- dcast(molten_fries, time + treatment + subject + variable~rep, mean, value.var="value", na.rm=TRUE)
head(cast_fries)

  time treatment subject variable    1    2
1    1         1       3   potato  2.9 14.0
2    1         1       3  buttery  0.0  0.0
3    1         1       3   grassy  0.0  0.0
4    1         1       3   rancid  0.0  1.1
5    1         1       3   painty  5.5  0.0
6    1         1      10   potato 11.0  9.9

Casting French fries data

  • we rename those new columns to be rep1 and rep2
colnames(cast_fries) <- c("time", "treatment", "subject" , "variable", "rep1","rep2")
head(cast_fries)

  time treatment subject variable rep1 rep2
1    1         1       3   potato  2.9 14.0
2    1         1       3  buttery  0.0  0.0
3    1         1       3   grassy  0.0  0.0
4    1         1       3   rancid  0.0  1.1
5    1         1       3   painty  5.5  0.0
6    1         1      10   potato 11.0  9.9
  • now the data is ready to be plotted

Plotting French fries data

ggplot(cast_fries, aes(rep1, rep2)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow=1)

  • The correlation looks strong for potatoey and buttery, and poor for rancid and painty

Plotting French fries data

ggplot(cast_fries, aes(rep1, rep2, color=treatment)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow=1)

  • Similar behavior is observed for each treatment

Transforming data

ggplot(sdat, aes(x)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..))+
  geom_density(color='hotpink', size=1.1)


ggplot(sdat, aes(log(x+0.5))) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..))+
  geom_density(color='hotpink', size=1.1)

Transforming data
